## Why use WhatsApp for community organizing?

WhatsApp is the most popular mobile messaging app worldwide, with over three billion monthly active users ([March 2025](https://www.statista.com/statistics/260819/number-of-monthly-active-whatsapp-users/)). India, with 854 million users, has the highest [number of users by country](https://worldpopulationreview.com/country-rankings/whatsapp-users-by-country), followed by Brazil (148 million), Indonesia (112 million), the United States (98 million) and The Philippines (88 million). 

The app is widely accessible in that it uses little mobile data and while it may not offer the digital security of alternatives like [Signal](https://signal.org/), it still offers end-to-end encryption on all messages, chats and calls, making it more secure than Facebook Messenger, Slack or SMS. 

[Engagement rates](https://m.aisensy.com/blog/whatsapp-statistics-for-businesses/) on WhatsApp are unmatched by other messaging apps, and much higher than on email and SMS. Messages on WhatsApp have a 98% open rate -  5 times more than emails and SMS. Click-through rates range from 45-60% compared to 2-5% on email and SMS.

This makes WhatsApp an attractive app for advocacy and movement building. WhatsApp can be used as a platform for supporter community building, to activate distributed networks, as well as for communication between campaigners and a channel for crowdsourced knowledge. 

Platforms like **Belcoda** build on these strengths, helping grassroots organizations use WhatsApp effectively for community organizing, event sign-ups, and taking action. 

